{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530447"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:06:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:06:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14544"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14544"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.73,0.12,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43537"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice on contraception. She stopped the combined oral contraceptive pill two years ago due to weight gain and is concerned about gaining weight again when commencing a new contraceptive. She was using the withdrawal method however four months ago required a medical termination of pregnancy, and is fearful of further unplanned pregnancy. She is not currently in a relationship and has not been sexually active in the past three months. She has a regular 28-day menstrual cycle and has always had heavy flow on the first three days, occasionally having flooding or missing days of work due to this. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She smokes five cigarettes per day and drinks four units of alcohol per week. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits and a BMI of 20 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate contraceptive recommendation for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Consistent condom use","Depot medroxyprogesterone acetate injection","Levonorgestrel intrauterine system","Copper intrauterine device","Progestogen-only pill"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented for advice about contraception with three main concerns. Firstly, she requires highly effective contraception due to her recent unplanned pregnancy and fear of future pregnancies. Secondly, she has identified previous weight gain that she attributed to the combined oral contraceptive pill (COCP). Finally, whilst it is not one of her presenting issues, she mentions that she has heavy menstrual bleeding. She should be provided statistics about weight gain and the contraception effects for each option as it is her main concern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor this patient, the \u003Cstrong\u003Elevonorgestrel intrauterine system (LNG-IUS)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate recommendation. It addresses her need for highly effective contraception while also significantly reducing her heavy menstrual bleeding. The LNG-IUS is a long-acting reversible contraception (LARC) method that releases a small amount of progestogen locally in the uterus, resulting in fewer systemic side effects compared to combined oral contraceptives. It can reduce menstrual blood loss by up to 90% after 12 months of use, which would be beneficial for this patient who experiences heavy periods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsistent condom use\u003C/strong\u003E, while important for protection against sexually transmitted infections, is not the most reliable method of contraception when used alone. Condom use has a higher failure rate compared to hormonal methods or IUDs, especially with typical use. For a patient who is adamant about avoiding pregnancy, a more effective and reliable method is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepot medroxyprogesterone acetate injection\u003C/strong\u003E is a progestogen-only contraceptive that is administered every 12 weeks. While effective for contraception, it is associated with weight gain in many users and can cause irregular bleeding patterns, particularly in the first few months of use. Given this patient\u0027s specific concern about weight gain, this would not be an ideal choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecopper intrauterine device\u003C/strong\u003E is a highly effective non-hormonal LARC option. However, it can increase menstrual bleeding and cramping, which would not be beneficial for a patient who already experiences heavy periods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogestogen-only pill\u003C/strong\u003E requires strict adherence to timing (must be taken within the same 3-hour window daily) to maintain efficacy. It may cause irregular bleeding patterns and does not reliably reduce menstrual blood loss. Given the patient\u0027s history of heavy menstrual bleeding and desire for highly effective contraception, this would not be the optimal choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe LNG-IUS offers several advantages in this case: it is highly effective at preventing pregnancy, it can significantly reduce menstrual bleeding, and it delivers a lower dose of hormone locally, which may result in fewer systemic side effects. It\u0027s important to counsel the patient about the potential side effects and benefits of the LNG-IUS, addressing her concerns about weight gain, and explaining how it differs from oral contraceptives. This approach can help alleviate her hesitancy and enable her to make an informed decision about her contraceptive choice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Long-acting reversible contraception (LARC) methods are highly effective and have fewer side effects than combined oral contraceptives.","The levonorgestrel intrauterine system (LNG-IUS) is an excellent option for contraception for women with heavy menstrual bleeding, as it can significantly reduce menstrual blood loss.","Patient education and counselling are crucial in addressing concerns and misconceptions about hormonal contraception."],"references":["Goldhammer DL, Fraser C, Wigginton B, Harris ML, Bateson D, Loxton D, Stewart M, Coombe J, Lucke JC. What do young Australian women want (when talking to doctors about contraception)? BMC Fam Pract. 2017 Mar 15;18(1):35. doi: 10.1186/s12875-017-0616-2. PMID: 28298197; PMCID: PMC5353872. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5353872/","Family Planning NSW. Contraception in Australia 2005-2018. Ashfield, Sydney: FPNSW; 2020. Available at: https://www.fpnsw.org.au/sites/default/files/assets/Contraception-in-Australia_2005-2018_v20200716.pdf","Claringbold L, Sanci L, Temple-Smith M. Factors influencing young womens contraceptive choices [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/factors-influencing-young-womens-contraceptive-cho"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14544"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-08T06:28:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-08T06:29:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7237"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ